		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=380403"><span id=>lykanthropus</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br>2 posts
		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.00]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=lykanthropus&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Probably one of the more important differences about having faster 1handed weapons as opposed to slower 2handed has more to do with the creature your fighting than how much DPS your doing.&nbsp;&nbsp;Its called Reposte.  It is when a mob instantly returns or essentially gets an extra attack on you just because you decided to smack it; as if the mobs are not uber enough.  Once you realize that mobs your fighting, unlike your scrawny warrior self, will land 99.9% of their normal hits and repostes and are inherently hasted or haste buffed you begin to realize that doing more damage with less hits is easier on your hp and hencefore easier on your healers.  The main concern about slow weapon delay occurs when over agressive casters agro the mobs onto them and then blame it on the warrior for not holding agro.  This occurs usually during a power level session when the group wants to agressively pull or chain pull mobs.  This is very simple to overcome if casters are smart and it simply means wait a few seconds before they cast.  Also, before the new combat abilities came out warriors only had a measly Taunt button; thats it Taunt.  Ok and kick.  And ok slam if your a fat char.  Anyway, I found out that simply continuously Taunting actually was not as useful as waiting until you lost agro and then taunt the creature. If Taunt was success it should put you back on the top of agro list.  The problem with continuously Taunting at high levels was that the time delay between refresh on Taunt could be too long and a caster could die in that time.  So, timing your taunt is critical.  Anyway,  now with combat abilities Provoke line you have even better way to taunt.  And then all the Anger weapon augments now as well.  Another thing about warriors is that for the most part they are a single mob fighter.  Meaning that when your fighting a mob you are responsible for that mob and any dangling mobs that may insidently be smacking you may or may not decide to stay smacking you for long.  The main thing is that you stick to the mob your attacking.  Ya occasionlly you can switch mobs and maintain agro between 2 mobs but for the most part the casters should be able to control the adds.  Anyway, i'm not sure if i have a point to be made but from the above it can be concluded that alot about how good a warrior is, is dependent on the quality of the other members knowledge/abilities in the group and understanding the mobs they are fighting.  Basically, a Paly or Sk can build so much agro from stuns or snares that the casters can begin nuking almost instantly whereas with the warrior main they will have to wait a time delay.  This time delay can change from mob to mob and from mob type to mob type and at changes in warrior levels.<br><br>ok i'm done rambling</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 width="100%"><tr><td id=fs8></td><td align=right id=fs8 >0 Replies</td></tr></table></td></tr></table><tr><td>
